│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/SimplifyIndVar.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.             │
│ Understanding the Issue:\n- The reproducer shows IndVarSimplify turns a loop  │
│ computing srem i32 729259140, %phi into returning the constant 729259140.     │
│ This is wrong: the original returns 130, as confirmed by Alive2.\n- The first │
│ transformation is in SimplifyIndvar::simplifyIVRemainder, which simplifies    │
│ srem to urem when both operands are known non-negative.\n- In this case, %phi │
│ (the divisor) can be negative (initially -173, and then 0 or negative         │
│ afterward). Replacing srem with urem changes semantics: urem interprets a     │
│ negative divisor as a huge unsigned number, making the remainder equal to the │
│ numerator, leading to the observed miscompile.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n-  │
│ ScalarEvolution prints %phi’s SCEV as (-173 + (-1 * zext(...)))<nuw><nsw>,    │
│ which is non-positive. The loop trip count is 0, which is correct.\n- The log │
│ shows \"INDVARS: Simplified srem\" immediately followed by replacing the loop │
│ exit condition with true, and ultimately emitting ret i32 729259140. This     │
│ indicates the urem transformation occurred first and then SCEV concluded the  │
│ remainder equals the numerator, folding it to a constant.\n- GDB confirms the │
│ replacement path: simplifyIVRemainder called replaceSRemWithURem at line 412. │
│ A direct evaluation shows SE->isKnownNonNegative(D) returned true at that     │
│ point, despite D (%phi) being negative on entry.\n\n3. Root Cause             │
│ Analysis:\n- The indvars logic uses only SCEV’s isKnownNonNegative to justify │
│ srem → urem. In this case SCEV incorrectly classifies the loop-varying        │
│ divisor as non-negative at the remainder’s program point. Whether this is an  │
│ underlying SCEV bug or an overly aggressive use in indvars, relying solely on │
│ SCEV here is unsafe for a value that is negative along some paths.\n- By      │
│ converting to urem under a false non-negativity assumption, the pass changes  │
│ semantics: positive % N (signed, N negative) ≠ positive % N (unsigned, N      │
│ interpreted as large). This cascades to the incorrect constant folding of the │
│ srem result and thus the wrong return value.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n-  │
│ File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/SimplifyIndVar.cpp\n- Function:               │
│ SimplifyIndvar::simplifyIVRemainder\n- Location: Around the final block that  │
│ attempts srem → urem replacement (current lines ~403–413). Add a              │
│ conservative, IR-level check using ValueTracking to double-check              │
│ non-negativity of the divisor at the instruction point, in addition to the    │
│ SCEV check. This guards against SCEV misclassification.\n\nEdit:\nReplace the │
│ tail block:\n  // Try to replace SRem with URem, if both N and D are known    │
│ non-negative.\n  // Since we had already check N, we only need to check D     │
│ now\n  if (!IsSigned || !SE->isKnownNonNegative(D))\n    return;\n\n          │
│ replaceSRemWithURem(Rem);\n\nWith the following:\n  // Try to replace SRem    │
│ with URem if both N and D are provably non-negative.\n  // Since we already   │
│ checked N for the signed case above, only check D now.\n  if (!IsSigned)\n    │
│ return;\n\n  // First, require SCEV to prove non-negativity of D.\n  if       │
│ (!SE->isKnownNonNegative(D))\n    return;\n\n  // Be conservative: also       │
│ require IR-level proof of non-negativity at this\n  // program point. SCEV    │
│ can occasionally over-approximate for loop-varying\n  // values. Guard with   │
│ ValueTracking.\n  const DataLayout &DL = Rem->getModule()->getDataLayout();\n │
│ if (!isKnownNonNegative(DValue, DL, /*Depth=*/0, Rem, /*AC=*/nullptr, DT))\n  │
│ return;\n\n  replaceSRemWithURem(Rem);\n\nNotes:\n- ValueTracking.h is        │
│ already included in this file.\n- We obtain DL from the module via            │
│ Rem->getModule()->getDataLayout().\n- We use the current instruction Rem and  │
│ the pass’s DT; AC is not strictly necessary.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy adding a   │
│ second, IR-level non-negativity check for the divisor before converting srem  │
│ to urem, we avoid miscompiles when SCEV misclassifies a loop-varying divisor. │
│ In the provided reproducer, %phi is not provably non-negative by              │
│ ValueTracking, so the conversion is skipped. The pass can still simplify the  │
│ exit condition (which is correct), and it will not incorrectly fold the       │
│ remainder to the numerator, preserving the correct return value (130). This   │
│ is a conservative fix localized to indvars that avoids depending solely on    │
│ SCEV for a semantics-changing transformation."})                              │
